      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Is the ZV-E10 good for serious vlogging?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Yes! It's designed specifically for vlogging with a flip screen,
              Product Showcase mode, and excellent autofocus. The lack of IBIS
              means you'll need a gimbal or electronic stabilization for walking
              shots. For stationary talking-head videos, it's unbeatable at this
              price.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Should I get the ZV-E10 or ZV-E10 II?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              If you can afford it, get the ZV-E10 II. It adds in-body
              stabilization, better battery life, and AI autofocus. But the
              original ZV-E10 is still excellent and now costs $200-300 less.
              For tripod work or gimbal use, the original is a smart budget
              pick.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              What lens should I buy first for vlogging?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              The Sony 16-50mm power zoom kit lens is actually good for
              vloggingâ€”it's lightweight and the power zoom is smooth. For better
              low-light and bokeh, upgrade to the Sigma 16mm f/1.4 (wide angle
              for arm's length) or Sony 35mm f/1.8 (tighter framing, more
              cinematic).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Does the ZV-E10 have good low-light performance?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              It's decent but not exceptional. The APS-C sensor is smaller than
              full-frame, so you'll see noise above ISO 3200. With a fast lens
              (f/1.4) and proper lighting, it handles indoor shooting well. For
              nighttime vlogging, consider adding a small LED panel.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Can I livestream with the ZV-E10?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Yes, using the USB-C port with Sony's Imaging Edge Webcam software
              (free). It works perfectly with OBS, Zoom, and YouTube Live. The
              camera can run off USB power indefinitely, so battery life isn't a
              concern during streams. Quality is far better than any webcam.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

